The avowed Puritanism of which this is characteristic, is not decrepit. It has in its ranks to-day a new movement of intense vitality.

It is not alone with Puritanism in its naked form that this sin lies of offering a maimed sacrifice, or, in other words, giving to God a part which purports to be the .whole. The majority of the religious in all churches and sects assume that prayer for, and interest in, the arts are optional. Yet I cannot see that there is any escape from the facts. God has chosen to so make men that the theatre‚ the libmry, the concert-mom, the joy of the eye and the dance, are influences of untold strength.
